                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 837.00/541.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-15">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">January</hi> 15, 1912</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President on the 15th issued a decree forbidding officers of Army and Rural
                    Guard from participation in politics; this was already forbidden by military
                    law. The decree also forbids their attendance at meetings of the Veterans’
                    Association, whose leaders declare that unless the decree is revoked they will
                    go to any lengths to obtain their end. I earnestly suggest advisability of a
                    decided stand at this time on our part. Should our intention to support the
                    President be made known it would probably have a discouraging effect on those
                    wishing to provoke intervention. Threatening speeches made by prominent
                    veterans. Situation now more alarming than at any previous time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Beaupré</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
